Using set theory, the given statement can be represented as follows:

Roses = {R1, R2,..., Rn}
Flowers = {F1, F2,..., Fl}
quickly fading flowers = {F1, F2,..., Fl} ⊆ Flowers
roses = {R1, R2,..., Rn} ⊆ Flowers
All roses are flowers = Roses ∩ Flowers = {R1, R2,..., Rn}
some flowers fade quickly = quickly fading flowers ∩ Flowers = {F1, F2,..., Fl}

Based on the given statement and its representation using sets, the conclusion "some roses fade quickly" can be derived as follows:

some roses are quickly fading flowers = {R1, R2,..., Rn} ∩ quickly fading flowers = R1 ∩ quickly fading flowers ∩ R2 ∩ quickly fading flowers ∩... ∩ Rn ∩ quickly fading flowers
                  = R1 ∩ {F1, F2,..., Fl} ∩ R2 ∩ {F1, F2,..., Fl} ∩... ∩ Rn ∩ {F1, F2,..., Fl}

Therefore, the answer to the given statement is YES. It can be inferred that since all roses are flowers and some flowers fade quickly, some roses must also fade quickly.
